<h1>2.3 Nouns</h1>
<p>Status: <em>draft</em></p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>n</strong>
(noun)</p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>d</strong> (dual), <strong>p</strong>
(plural)</p></li>
<li><p>gender: <strong>7th</strong>; letters: <strong>m</strong>
(masculine), <strong>f</strong> (feminine), <strong>n</strong>
(neuter)</p></li>
<li><p>case: <strong>8th</strong>; letters: <strong>n</strong>
(nominative), <strong>g</strong> (genitive), <strong>d</strong>
(dative), <strong>a</strong> (accusative), <strong>v</strong>
(vocative)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> n-s—mn- (noun, singular,
masculine, nominative)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Nouns in AG are usually treated as inflecting in three
<strong>declensions</strong>. The declensions have their own sets of
endings.</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>1st declension (a-declension)
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.1" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.1">see Smyth
§211ff.</a></li>
<li>2nd declension (o-declension)
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.2" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.2">see Smyth
§</a></li>
<li>3rd declension (stem ending in a consonant or ι or υ (or semivowels
y or ϝ))
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.5" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.5">see
Smyth</a></li>
</ol>
<p>However, in postclassical Greek the noun declension underwent various
changes (e.g.&nbsp;gradual merger of masculine and feminine nouns of the
first and third declensions and a new oxytone masculine declension in
-ᾶς <strong>[XXXsiis eihän tuo ole oxytone vaan
perispomenon…])</strong>. Therefore, for example the Cambridge Grammar
of Medieval and Early Modern Greek has chosen to present noun inflection
with different paradigms closer to Standard Modern Greek grammars (<span class="citation" data-cites="holton2019">Holton et al. (2019)</span> II
253–254). These changes were caused by changes in pronunciation and
e.g.&nbsp;the loss of vowel length distinction (see <a href="/grammar/7" data-link="" data-url="grammar/7">1.2</a> XXX in
Phonology) and for this reason the papyri are an important testimony for
the timeline of the changes appearing in texts of different registers.
The written standard for the most part still appears as trying to follow
the CG declension, and we will present our material following the three
declensions familiar from the school grammars, but discussing the
possible markers of change visible in papyri.</p>
<p><strong>tulisiko haut erikseen jokaisesta sijamuodosta?</strong></p>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<ul>
<li>How is the nominal morphology in Egyptian different from Greek and
how are Egyptian words integrated in Greek papyri?</li>
</ul>
